library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(GGally)
library(modelr)
library(broom)
library(glmulti)
library(caret)
oj <- read_csv("data/orange_juice.csv") %>% 
  clean_names()
oj <- oj %>% 
  mutate(purchase_mm = factor(if_else(purchase == "MM", "Yes","No"))) %>% 
  select(-purchase)
oj_factored <- oj %>% 
  mutate(store_id = factor(store_id),
         special_ch = factor(special_ch),
         special_mm = factor(special_mm),
         store7 = factor(store7),
         store = factor(store)
         ) %>% 
  select(-c(price_ch, price_mm, disc_ch, disc_mm, store7, price_diff, store))
oj_factored %>% 
  distinct(store_id)
alias(purchase_mm ~ ., data = oj_factored)
using type = "numeric" with a factor response will be ignored‘-’ not meaningful for factors
Model :
purchase_mm ~ weekof_purchase + store_id + special_ch + special_mm + 
    loyal_ch + sale_price_mm + sale_price_ch + pct_disc_mm + 
    pct_disc_ch + list_price_diff
oj_factored %>% 
  ggpairs()

There seems to be possible correlation with store_id, special_ch, special_mm, loyal_ch. Surprisingly, the price does not seem to have that great an effect?

Cross Validation

train_control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", 
                              number = 5,
                              repeats = 100,
                              savePredictions = TRUE, 
                              classProbs = TRUE, 
                              summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)

model <- train(purchase_mm ~ loyal_ch + sale_price_mm + sale_price_ch,
               data = oj_factored,
               trControl = train_control,
               method = "glm",
               family = binomial(link = 'logit'))

Text-Mining Section

library(janeaustenr)
library(text2vec)
library(tidyr)
library(tidytext)
pride_tibble <- tibble(
  line = prideprejudice,
  line_no = 1:length(prideprejudice)
)
sense_tibble <- tibble(
  line = sensesensibility,
  line_no = seq(from = (length(prideprejudice) + 1), to = (length(prideprejudice) + length(sensesensibility)), by = 1)
)
books <- bind_rows(pride_tibble, sense_tibble)

Find the most common words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility

books <- books %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, line) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE)

Find the most common words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility, not including stop words.

books %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"

Find the most common sentiment words in both Pride & Prejudice and Sense & Sensibility.

books %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
  left_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>% 
  filter(sentiment == "negative" | sentiment == "positive")
Joining, by = "word"
Joining, by = "word"
